===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}

{{liushu|p}} of a ritual axe made perhaps of jade, symbols of the king's power. A ceremonial axe was kept near the throne, and was used for performing rituals in ancient China.

The traditional interpretation (most likely a folk etymology given the original appearance of the character) is that the character metaphorically indicates the king or emperor according to the ancient Chinese thought: three horizontal strokes represent Heaven, Man and Earth, and the vertical stroke is the king or emperor, the one who connects them together. However, compare {{l|zh|天}} (a man with a horizontal stroke above his head to indicate the sky).

Unrelated to {{m|zh|玉|t=a string with three pieces of jade}} and {{m|zh|主|t=master}}; partly related to [[士]] (a war axe and, perhaps, sometimes a variant of 王), to [[戉]] (an axe drawn vertically), to the inner component of {{m|zh|匡|t=square‑shaped bamboo basket}}, and to the right component of [[往]] (< [[𢓸]]).

===Etymology 1===
{{unc|zh}}. There are many proposed etymologies:
* {{zh-ref|Sagart and Baxter (2009)}} compare it to {{cog|bo|གོང་མ||tr=gong ma|[[superior]] [[one]]}}.
* {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} compares it to {{cog|bo|དབང||tr=dbang|[[strength]], [[power]]}} and {{cog|my|အန်||tr=an|strength, power}}, which derive from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*d-baŋ||strength, power}}. However, reconstructing the {{cog|och|-}} as ''*waŋ'', he notes the mismatch between Old Chinese ''*w-'' vs. Tibetan ''*b-'' (unless ''*dw-'' can become ''db-''; for possible ''*b- ~ * w-'' variation, see {{zh-l|*花}}). He also compares it to {{w|Konyak languages|Proto-Northern Naga}} {{m|und|*waŋ||[[chief]]}}.
* {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} alternatively proposes a connection to {{cog|okz|vāṅ}}, {{m|okz|vaṅ|pos=modern {{cog|km|វាំង|tr=veăng}}, “[[royal]] [[palace]]”}}, which he considers to be cognate with {{cog|km|ហ្លួង||tr=hluŏng|king}}. This is perhaps supported by a {{w|Chinese bronze inscriptions|bronze inscription}} where {{lang|zh|王}} refers to a place, not the {{w|Zhou dynasty|Zhou}} king ({{zh-ref|Shaughnessy, 1991}}). The semantic shift from "palace" to "king" parallels {{cog|egy|pr-ꜥꜣ||[[pharaoh]]|lit=palace}}, from {{m|egy|pr||house}} + {{m|egy|ꜥꜣ||great, big}}. The connection to the {{cog|okz|-}} word would thus relate it to {{cog|mkh-pro|*waŋ|*waŋ ~ *waaŋ|enclosure; to go round}}, which is part of a larger {{cog|aav}} word family, including {{och-l|營||to encamp; to surround}} and {{och-l|環||ring}}. {{zh-ref|Bodman (1980)}} connects {{lang|zh|王}} with {{och-l|皇|sovereign}}, which {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} connects to this word family.
* Speculations exist about its connection to {{och-l|尪|[[lame]], [[crippled]]}} and {{och-l|狂|id=1|[[mad]]}}, based on theories about the connection between ancient Chinese kingship and shamanism ({{zh-ref|Keightley, 1995}}).

